  "prompt": "Who are all the countries in debt to?",
  "response": "Countries typically owe debt to a variety of creditors, which can be broadly categorized as follows:\n\n1. **Domestic Lenders**: These include domestic banks, private investors, and financial institutions within the country. Governments issue bonds that are purchased by these entities.\n\n2. **Foreign Governments and International Institutions**: Countries often borrow from other countries, either directly or through international institutions. Major international creditors include the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the World Bank, and regional development banks like the European Investment Bank or the Asian Development Bank.\n\n3. **Private Foreign Investors**: These can include foreign banks, hedge funds, and institutional investors who buy government bonds issued in international markets. \n\n4. **Multilateral Organizations**: These are organizations formed by multiple countries that provide financial assistance to member countries. Examples include the IMF and World Bank, as well as regional development banks.\n\n5. **Bilateral Agreements**: Sometimes countries borrow through bilateral agreements, where one country lends directly to another. China, for example, has become a prominent lender to various countries through such bilateral agreements.\n\nThe exact composition of a country's debt varies significantly depending on its economic policies, credibility, and relationship with international lenders and markets.",
